Applying the Law of Sines to triangle $ABD$ gives
\[\frac{BD}{\sin \angle BAD} = \frac{AD}{\sin \angle ABD}.\]Since $\angle BAD = 90^\circ - 2x$ and $\angle ABD = x,$
\[\frac{BD}{\cos 2x} = \frac{AD}{\sin x}.\]Substituting $AD = \frac{2}{3} CD$ gives
\[\frac{BD}{\cos 2x} = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{CD}{\sin x}.\]Hence,
\[\frac{BD}{CD} = \frac{2 \sin x}{3 \cos 2x} = \frac{2 \sin x}{3 (1 - 2 \sin^2 x)} = \frac{2}{3} \cdot \frac{1}{\frac{1}{2} - \frac{3}{2} \cos 2x}.\]From the Law of Cosines on triangle $ABC,$
\[BC^2 = AC^2 + AB^2 = AB^2 + (AB - BC)^2.\]It follows that $BC^2 = AB^2 + (AB - BC)^2,$ so $BC = \frac{AB}{2} \left( 3 - \sqrt{5} \right).$

Then
\[\tan x = \frac{AD}{CD} = \frac{2 \sin x}{3 \cos 2x}.\]Solving gives $\sin x = \frac{3}{\sqrt{65}},$ so $\cos x = \frac{4}{\sqrt{65}}.$ Then $\sin 2x = \frac{6}{\sqrt{65}}$ and $\cos 2x = \frac{33}{65}.$ Also, $\cos 3x = 4 \cos^3 x - 3 \cos x = \frac{149}{65}.$ Therefore,
\[\frac{CD}{BD} = \frac{1/\tan x - 1}{1 + 1/\tan x} = \frac{\frac{\sqrt{65}}{3} - 1}{\frac{\sqrt{65}}{3} + 1} = \boxed{\frac{4 - \sqrt{65}}{7}}.\]```

